{"title_page": "Michael D'Andrea", "text_new": "'''Michael D'Andrea''' was an officer of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], who in 2017 was appointed to head the agency's Iran Mission Center.<ref name=\"NYT1\">{{cite news |title=C.I.A. Names New Iran Chief in a Sign of Trump's Hard Line |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/02/world/middleeast/cia-iran-dark-prince-michael-dandrea.html |first1=Matthew |last1=Rosenberg |first2=Adam |last2=Goldman |date=June 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602174554/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/02/world/middleeast/cia-iran-dark-prince-michael-dandrea.html |archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> He was a major figure in the [[search for Osama bin Laden]], as well as the American [[drone strike]] [[targeted killing]] campaign.<ref name=\"NYT1\"/> It is speculated that Michael D'Andrea was killed in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://21stcenturywire.com/2020/02/02/the-mysterious-michael-dandrea-was-cias-iran-chief-really-shot-down-over-afghanistan/|title=The Mysterious Michael D\u2019Andrea: Was CIA's Iran Chief Really Shot Down Over Afghanistan?|last=21wire|date=2020-02-02|website=21st Century Wire|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nD'Andrea was raised in [[Northern Virginia]].<ref name=\"NYT1\"/> He met his wife while working overseas with the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], and converted to [[Islam]] in order to marry her.<ref name=\"NYT1\"/><ref name=\"Gawker\">{{cite news |url=http://gawker.com/why-wont-the-post-name-cia-counterterrorism-chief-micha-1693833306 |title=Why Won't the Post Name CIA Counterterrorism Chief Michael D'Andrea? |first=John |last=Cook |publisher=[[Gawker]] |date=March 26, 2015 |access-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> His wife, Faridah Currimjee D'Andrea is a daughter of a wealthy Muslim family from [[Mauritius]] with [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] origins.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.iransview.com/ayatollah-mikes-face-revealed-irans-view/1672/ |title=CIA Agent Ayatollah Mike's Face Revealed: Iran's View|publisher=[[Iran's View]] |date=June 3, 2017 |access-date=June 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nD'Andrea joined the CIA in 1979, and he was considered an underperformer at [[Camp Peary]].<ref name=\"WashPoRoger\"/> D'Andrea reportedly began his overseas career in [[Africa]], and he is listed as a foreign service officer at the [[Embassy of the United States, Dar es Salaam|Embassy of the United States in Dar es Salaam]], [[Tanzania]].<ref name=\"WashPoRoger\"/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QOCvcA6s1W4C&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113|title=Key Officers of Foreign Service Posts: Guide for Business Representatives|last=|first=|publisher=DIANE Publishing Company|year=1998|isbn=9780788148682|location=|page=113|pages=|quote=RAO: Michael A. D'Andrea}}</ref> D'Andrea previously served as chief of station in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]] and later in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]].<ref name=\"WashPoRoger\"/><ref name=\"Newsweek\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newsweek.com/cia-michael-dandrea-new-york-times-mark-mazzetti-drones-pakistan-al-qaeda-war-475180 |magazine=[[Newsweek]] |title=Outing the CIA's 'Undertaker' |first=Nicholas |last=Schou |date=June 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602185005/http://www.newsweek.com/cia-michael-dandrea-new-york-times-mark-mazzetti-drones-pakistan-al-qaeda-war-475180 |archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> D'Andrea was reportedly one of the CIA officials who failed to track [[Nawaf al-Hazmi]], who would later participate in the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\nD'Andrea became head of the CIA's [[Counterterrorism Center]] in 2006, replacing [[Robert Grenier (CIA)|Robert Grenier]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hh9-BAAAQBAJ&pg=PT260&lpg=PT260&dq=%22Mike+D%E2%80%99Andrea%22+CIA&source=bl&ots=AEYpOqgQRt&sig=oSq6lW8MBrWGxPO2gzPv2rrWnXE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1u4zU-J_UAhUP0IMKHTooBHYQ6AEITTAH#v=onepage&q=%22Mike%20D%E2%80%99Andrea%22%20CIA&f=false |title=Kill Chain: The Rise of the High-Tech Assassins |first=Andrew |last=Cockburn |publisher=[[Henry Holt and Company]] |year=2015 |isbn=9780805099270}}</ref> During his nine-year tenure, D'Andrea presided over hundreds of American drone strikes in [[Pakistan]] and [[Yemen]], advocating for the program to the [[United States Congress]].<ref name=\"NYT1\"/><ref name=\"NYT_Drone\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/26/us/politics/deep-support-in-washington-for-cias-drone-missions.html?smid=tw-share |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=Deep Support in Washington for C.I.A.'s Drone Missions |first=Mark |last=Mazzetti |first2=Matthew |last2=Apuzzo |date=April 25, 2015 |access-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> In 2015, leadership of the drone program was passed to Chris Wood, following bureaucratic reshuffling by [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|Director]] [[John O. Brennan]].<ref name=\"NYT_Drone\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-drone-strikes-plummet-as-white-house-shifts-authority-to-pentagon/2016/06/16/e0b28e90-335f-11e6-8ff7-7b6c1998b7a0_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |quote=\"I suspect that has an awful lot to do with it,\" said a former senior U.S. official who was involved in CIA and Pentagon discussions about collaboration in Yemen, and described Michael D'Andrea, the former CTC chief, as an obstacle. D'Andrea was replaced by Chris Wood, a longtime CIA officer who is widely considered more collegial and willing to compromise with U.S. military officials. |title=Why CIA drone strikes have plummeted |first=Greg |last=Miller |date=June 16, 2016}}</ref> During his time at the Counterterrorism Center many reporters referred to him only by the codename \"Roger\", which was considered unusual for an official not posted overseas.<ref name=\"Gawker\">{{cite news |url=http://gawker.com/why-wont-the-post-name-cia-counterterrorism-chief-micha-1693833306 |title=Why Won't the Post Name CIA Counterterrorism Chief Michael D'Andrea? |first=John |last=Cook |publisher=[[Gawker]] |date=March 26, 2015 |access-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"WashPoRoger\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/at-cia-a-convert-to-islam-leads-the-terrorism-hunt/2012/03/23/gIQA2mSqYS_story.html|title=At CIA, a convert to Islam leads the terrorism hunt|last=Miller|first=Greg|date=March 24, 2012|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 13, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\nDuring the hunt for Osama bin Laden, D'Andrea directed an [[analysis of competing hypotheses]] as to who, besides [[Osama bin Laden]], could be in the targeted [[Osama bin Laden's compound in Abbottabad|compound in Abbottabad]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Red Team: How to Succeed By Thinking Like the Enemy |first=Micah |last=Zenko|authorlink=Micah Zenko |pages=100\u2013101 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k20uCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=Michael+D%E2%80%99Andrea+CIA&source=bl&ots=KnoKg0oc_M&sig=5YO5ZOWJOeX6gMjmBqs7IU3FYBI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5ppr_7Z_UAhWD24MKHXOGBIs4FBDoAQhBMAY#v=onepage&q=Michael%20D%E2%80%99Andrea%20CIA&f=false |publisher=[[Basic Books]] |year=2015 |isbn=9780465073955}}</ref>\n\nD'Andrea's operatives also oversaw the interrogations of [[Abu Zubaydah]], [[Abd al-Rahim al-Nashiri]] and [[Khalid Shaikh Mohammed]], which were criticized in a [[Committee Study of the Central Intelligence Agency's Detention and Interrogation Program|United States Senate report]].<ref name=\"NYT1\"/><ref name=\"NYT_Drone\"/> He was reportedly involved in the assassination of [[Hezbollah]] member [[Imad Mughniyah]] in [[Damascus, Syria]].<ref name=\"NYT1\"/> He received much blame for the [[Camp Chapman attack]] in [[Khost Province|Khost]], [[Afghanistan]], when seven CIA operatives were killed by a [[suicide bomber]], who was allegedly backed by Pakistan's [[Inter-Services Intelligence|ISI]].<ref name=\"WashPoRoger\"/><ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\nHe has been nicknamed \"Ayatollah Mike.\"<ref name=\"NYT1\"/>\n\n== Speculated Death ==\nOn January 27, 2020, a US spy plane reportedly carrying CIA officials was downed over Afghanistan, with Michael D'Andrea said to have been among the passengers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200128-cia-chief-behind-soleimanis-assassination-killed-in-downed-plane-in-afghanistan/|title=CIA chief \u2018behind Soleimani\u2019s assassination\u2019 killed in downed plane in Afghanistan|date=2020-01-28|website=Middle East Monitor|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> The Taliban claimed credit for the downing, though it has also been speculated that Iran could have been involved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/02/cia-mystery-did-the-taliban-kill-ayatollah-mike-2/|title=CIA mystery: Did Iran kill \u2018Ayatollah Mike?\u2019|last=Makichuk|first=Dave|date=2020-02-06|website=Asia Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> When asked by media outlets to confirm whether Michael D'Andrea was killed in the downed plane, the CIA declined to answer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/iran-image-zero-dark-thirty-actor-claim-cia-agent-death-2020-1|title=Iranian state TV used a photo of an actor from 'Zero Dark Thirty' to spread a wild theory that a senior CIA official was killed in a plane crash in Afghanistan|last=Bostock|first=Bill|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> While the CIA has declined to confirm the report, news coverage has noted that \"If the CIA regional chief has not been killed in the plane crash, he has also not appeared in public to refute claims of his death.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crescent.icit-digital.org/articles/was-cia-regional-chief-d-andrea-killed-in-the-plane-crash-in-afghanistan|title=Was CIA regional chief D\u2019Andrea killed in the plane crash in Afghanistan?|website=Crescent International|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nD'Andrea was the inspiration for the character of \"The Wolf\" in [[Kathryn Bigelow|Kathryn Bigelow's]] ''[[Zero Dark Thirty]]''.<ref name=\"Gawker\"/><ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D'Andrea, Michael}}\n[[Category:People of the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n[[Category:People from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Michael D'Andrea''' was an officer of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], who in 2017 was appointed to head the agency's Iran Mission Center.<ref name=\"NYT1\">{{cite news |title=C.I.A. Names New Iran Chief in a Sign of Trump's Hard Line |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/02/world/middleeast/cia-iran-dark-prince-michael-dandrea.html |first1=Matthew |last1=Rosenberg |first2=Adam |last2=Goldman |date=June 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602174554/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/02/world/middleeast/cia-iran-dark-prince-michael-dandrea.html |archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> He was a major figure in the [[search for Osama bin Laden]], as well as the American [[drone strike]] [[targeted killing]] campaign.<ref name=\"NYT1\"/> It is speculated that Michael D'Andrea was killed in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://21stcenturywire.com/2020/02/02/the-mysterious-michael-dandrea-was-cias-iran-chief-really-shot-down-over-afghanistan/|title=The Mysterious Michael D\u2019Andrea: Was CIA's Iran Chief Really Shot Down Over Afghanistan?|last=21wire|date=2020-02-02|website=21st Century Wire|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nD'Andrea was raised in [[Northern Virginia]].<ref name=\"NYT1\"/> He met his wife while working overseas with the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], and converted to [[Islam]] in order to marry her.<ref name=\"NYT1\"/><ref name=\"Gawker\">{{cite news |url=http://gawker.com/why-wont-the-post-name-cia-counterterrorism-chief-micha-1693833306 |title=Why Won't the Post Name CIA Counterterrorism Chief Michael D'Andrea? |first=John |last=Cook |publisher=[[Gawker]] |date=March 26, 2015 |access-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> His wife, Faridah Currimjee D'Andrea is a daughter of a wealthy Muslim family from [[Mauritius]] with [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] origins.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.iransview.com/ayatollah-mikes-face-revealed-irans-view/1672/ |title=CIA Agent Ayatollah Mike's Face Revealed: Iran's View|publisher=[[Iran's View]] |date=June 3, 2017 |access-date=June 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nD'Andrea joined the CIA in 1979, and he was considered an underperformer at [[Camp Peary]].<ref name=\"WashPoRoger\"/> D'Andrea reportedly began his overseas career in [[Africa]], and he is listed as a foreign service officer at the [[Embassy of the United States, Dar es Salaam|Embassy of the United States in Dar es Salaam]], [[Tanzania]].<ref name=\"WashPoRoger\"/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QOCvcA6s1W4C&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113|title=Key Officers of Foreign Service Posts: Guide for Business Representatives|last=|first=|publisher=DIANE Publishing Company|year=1998|isbn=9780788148682|location=|page=113|pages=|quote=RAO: Michael A. D'Andrea}}</ref> D'Andrea previously served as chief of station in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]] and later in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]].<ref name=\"WashPoRoger\"/><ref name=\"Newsweek\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newsweek.com/cia-michael-dandrea-new-york-times-mark-mazzetti-drones-pakistan-al-qaeda-war-475180 |magazine=[[Newsweek]] |title=Outing the CIA's 'Undertaker' |first=Nicholas |last=Schou |date=June 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602185005/http://www.newsweek.com/cia-michael-dandrea-new-york-times-mark-mazzetti-drones-pakistan-al-qaeda-war-475180 |archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> D'Andrea was reportedly one of the CIA officials who failed to track [[Nawaf al-Hazmi]], who would later participate in the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\nD'Andrea became head of the CIA's [[Counterterrorism Center]] in 2006, replacing [[Robert Grenier (CIA)|Robert Grenier]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hh9-BAAAQBAJ&pg=PT260&lpg=PT260&dq=%22Mike+D%E2%80%99Andrea%22+CIA&source=bl&ots=AEYpOqgQRt&sig=oSq6lW8MBrWGxPO2gzPv2rrWnXE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1u4zU-J_UAhUP0IMKHTooBHYQ6AEITTAH#v=onepage&q=%22Mike%20D%E2%80%99Andrea%22%20CIA&f=false |title=Kill Chain: The Rise of the High-Tech Assassins |first=Andrew |last=Cockburn |publisher=[[Henry Holt and Company]] |year=2015 |isbn=9780805099270}}</ref> During his nine-year tenure, D'Andrea presided over hundreds of American drone strikes in [[Pakistan]] and [[Yemen]], advocating for the program to the [[United States Congress]].<ref name=\"NYT1\"/><ref name=\"NYT_Drone\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/26/us/politics/deep-support-in-washington-for-cias-drone-missions.html?smid=tw-share |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=Deep Support in Washington for C.I.A.'s Drone Missions |first=Mark |last=Mazzetti |first2=Matthew |last2=Apuzzo |date=April 25, 2015 |access-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> In 2015, leadership of the drone program was passed to Chris Wood, following bureaucratic reshuffling by [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|Director]] [[John O. Brennan]].<ref name=\"NYT_Drone\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-drone-strikes-plummet-as-white-house-shifts-authority-to-pentagon/2016/06/16/e0b28e90-335f-11e6-8ff7-7b6c1998b7a0_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |quote=\"I suspect that has an awful lot to do with it,\" said a former senior U.S. official who was involved in CIA and Pentagon discussions about collaboration in Yemen, and described Michael D'Andrea, the former CTC chief, as an obstacle. D'Andrea was replaced by Chris Wood, a longtime CIA officer who is widely considered more collegial and willing to compromise with U.S. military officials. |title=Why CIA drone strikes have plummeted |first=Greg |last=Miller |date=June 16, 2016}}</ref> During his time at the Counterterrorism Center many reporters referred to him only by the codename \"Roger\", which was considered unusual for an official not posted overseas.<ref name=\"Gawker\">{{cite news |url=http://gawker.com/why-wont-the-post-name-cia-counterterrorism-chief-micha-1693833306 |title=Why Won't the Post Name CIA Counterterrorism Chief Michael D'Andrea? |first=John |last=Cook |publisher=[[Gawker]] |date=March 26, 2015 |access-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"WashPoRoger\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/at-cia-a-convert-to-islam-leads-the-terrorism-hunt/2012/03/23/gIQA2mSqYS_story.html|title=At CIA, a convert to Islam leads the terrorism hunt|last=Miller|first=Greg|date=March 24, 2012|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 13, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\nDuring the hunt for Osama bin Laden, D'Andrea directed an [[analysis of competing hypotheses]] as to who, besides [[Osama bin Laden]], could be in the targeted [[Osama bin Laden's compound in Abbottabad|compound in Abbottabad]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Red Team: How to Succeed By Thinking Like the Enemy |first=Micah |last=Zenko|authorlink=Micah Zenko |pages=100\u2013101 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k20uCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=Michael+D%E2%80%99Andrea+CIA&source=bl&ots=KnoKg0oc_M&sig=5YO5ZOWJOeX6gMjmBqs7IU3FYBI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5ppr_7Z_UAhWD24MKHXOGBIs4FBDoAQhBMAY#v=onepage&q=Michael%20D%E2%80%99Andrea%20CIA&f=false |publisher=[[Basic Books]] |year=2015 |isbn=9780465073955}}</ref>\n\nD'Andrea's operatives also oversaw the interrogations of [[Abu Zubaydah]], [[Abd al-Rahim al-Nashiri]] and [[Khalid Shaikh Mohammed]], which were criticized in a [[Committee Study of the Central Intelligence Agency's Detention and Interrogation Program|United States Senate report]].<ref name=\"NYT1\"/><ref name=\"NYT_Drone\"/> He was reportedly involved in the assassination of [[Hezbollah]] member [[Imad Mughniyah]] in [[Damascus, Syria]].<ref name=\"NYT1\"/> He received much blame for the [[Camp Chapman attack]] in [[Khost Province|Khost]], [[Afghanistan]], when seven CIA operatives were killed by a [[suicide bomber]], who was allegedly backed by Pakistan's [[Inter-Services Intelligence|ISI]].<ref name=\"WashPoRoger\"/><ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\nHe has been nicknamed \"Ayatollah Mike.\"<ref name=\"NYT1\"/>\n\n== Speculated Death ==\nOn January 27, 2020, a US spy plane reportedly carrying CIA officials was downed over Afghanistan, with Michael D'Andrea said to have been among the passengers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200128-cia-chief-behind-soleimanis-assassination-killed-in-downed-plane-in-afghanistan/|title=CIA chief \u2018behind Soleimani\u2019s assassination\u2019 killed in downed plane in Afghanistan|date=2020-01-28|website=Middle East Monitor|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> The Taliban claimed credit for the downing, though it has also been speculated that Iran was involved. When asked by media outlets to confirm whether Michael D'Andrea was killed in the downed plane, the CIA declined to answer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/iran-image-zero-dark-thirty-actor-claim-cia-agent-death-2020-1|title=Iranian state TV used a photo of an actor from 'Zero Dark Thirty' to spread a wild theory that a senior CIA official was killed in a plane crash in Afghanistan|last=Bostock|first=Bill|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> While the CIA has declined to confirm the report, news coverage has noted that \"If the CIA regional chief has not been killed in the plane crash, he has also not appeared in public to refute claims of his death.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crescent.icit-digital.org/articles/was-cia-regional-chief-d-andrea-killed-in-the-plane-crash-in-afghanistan|title=Was CIA regional chief D\u2019Andrea killed in the plane crash in Afghanistan?|website=Crescent International|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nD'Andrea was the inspiration for the character of \"The Wolf\" in [[Kathryn Bigelow|Kathryn Bigelow's]] ''[[Zero Dark Thirty]]''.<ref name=\"Gawker\"/><ref name=\"Newsweek\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D'Andrea, Michael}}\n[[Category:People of the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n[[Category:People from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Nozoz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_D%27Andrea"}
